      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mideast Turmoil Is Like No Other</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>H Richard Friman letter comments on Anthony Lewis's column on Mideast turmoil (Oct 14) and his lament that 'there is no Palestinian Mandela'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''But There Is No Peace,'' by Anthony Lewis (column, Oct. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''But There Is No Peace,'' by Anthony Lewis (column, Oct. 14):</p>
        <p>Mr. Lewis's lament that ''there is no Palestinian Mandela,'' though personally compelling, suggests that the events in the Middle East are comparable to those in South Africa years earlier. But the analogy is flawed.</p>
        <p>Unlike South Africa, the contending parties in Israel seek separate states on the same territory. There is no discussion of a new Israel where Jew and Arab are equally empowered and where democratic elections could lead to a Palestinian government of the entire country.</p>
        <p>Yasir Arafat is clearly not Nelson Mandela, and neither is Ehud Barak an Israeli F. W. de Klerk. If they were different men, perhaps the current wave of violence in the Middle East could have been prevented. But Mr. Arafat and Mr. Barak are who they are, and Israel is not South Africa.</p>
        <p>H. RICHARD FRIMAN  Milwaukee, Oct. 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of political science at Marquette University.</p>
      </block>
